baseline: While pediatric mania and depression can be distinguished from each other, differentiating between unipolar major depressive disorder (unipolar MDD) and bipolar major depression (bipolar MDD) poses unique clinical and therapeutic challenges.
high_intensity: While pediatric mania and depression can be dramatically distinguished from each other, differentiating between unipolar major depressive disorder (unipolar MDD) and bipolar major depression (bipolar MDD) poses significant clinical and therapeutic challenges.
low_intensity: While pediatric mania and depression can be moderately distinguished from each other, differentiating between unipolar major depressive disorder (unipolar MDD) and bipolar major depression (bipolar MDD) poses some clinical and therapeutic challenges.

baseline: Unusually intense headaches may be contributing to depression in the headaches first group, although headaches causing depression may be infrequent.
high_intensity: Unusually severe headaches may be contributing to depression in the headaches first group, although headaches causing depression may be rare.
low_intensity: Unusually mild headaches may be contributing to depression in the headaches first group, although headaches causing depression may be infrequent.

baseline: Literature has shown that obesity, metabolic syndrome and inflammation are associated with depression, however, evidence suggests that these associations are specific to atypical depression.
high_intensity: Literature has shown that obesity, metabolic syndrome, and inflammation are associated with depression, however, compelling evidence suggests that these associations are specific to severe atypical depression.
low_intensity: Literature has shown that obesity, metabolic syndrome, and inflammation are associated with depression, however, some evidence suggests that these associations are specific to mild atypical depression.

baseline: Using a large sample from a PHP/IOP specifically designed for the treatment of eating disorders, the current study examines a variety of symptoms (eating disorder severity, quality of life, depression, etc.)
high_intensity: Using a large sample from a PHP/IOP specifically designed for the treatment of eating disorders, the current study examines a variety of severe symptoms (eating disorder severity, quality of life, depression, etc.)
low_intensity: Using a large sample from a PHP/IOP specifically designed for the treatment of eating disorders, the current study examines a variety of mild symptoms (eating disorder severity, quality of life, depression, etc.)

baseline: Self-esteem was strongly related to depression in both groups but was negatively related to theory of mind only for youth with ASD.
high_intensity: Self-esteem was intensely related to depression in both groups but was profoundly negatively related to theory of mind only for youth with ASD.
low_intensity: Self-esteem was somewhat related to depression in both groups but was slightly negatively related to theory of mind only for youth with ASD.
